TASK INSTRUCTIONS - PLEASE READ CAREFULLY! The goal of this study is to learn how mind wandering affects how you learn information during reading.

Mind wandering is a term used to describe what occurs when your attention wanders from a task. Sometimes when your mind wanders, you begin thinking about personal events or concerns rather than your task. At other times, your mind can wander because you are bored or tired and you don’t really know what you’re thinking about; all you know is that you are no longer thinking about your task.

Please press the space bar to continue.

In this task, you will read 4 passages and answer reading comprehension questions for each passage.

THE PASSAGES WILL BE PRESENTED IN A SENTENCE-BY-SENTENCE FASHION. PLEASE READ THE SENTENCES AT YOUR NORMAL READING PACE. ONCE YOU HAVE FINISHED READING ONE SENTENCE, PRESS THE SPACE BAR TO MOVE ON TO THE NEXT SENTENCE. Once you've read the sentence you MAY NOT GO BACK.

Please press the space bar to continue.

THE SET OF READING COMPREHENSION QUESTIONS FOR THAT PARTICULAR PASSAGE YOU’VE FINISHED READING WILL APPEAR AFTER EACH PASSAGE, not all together at the end. Like the sentences, once you've answered the questions you MAY NOT GO BACK TO CHANGE YOUR ANSWER.

Please press the space bar to continue.

Additionally, while you are reading you will be randomly interrupted and asked “WERE YOU MIND WANDERING WHEN YOU READ THE PREVIOUS SENTENCE?" You would have to choose either “Yes” or "No" by clicking on the appropriate option.

Please press the space bar to continue.

This entire task is self-paced. Though of course you should try NOT TO go over the task's ending time of 20 minutes. So try to do the task all the way through instead of taking too many small breaks in between. The task isn't long, so you should be able to do it without taking any breaks.

Please press the space bar to continue.
Please press the space bar to start reading the first passage.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 1
Marketing is a business activity that directs the flow of goods and services from a producer to a consumer or user.
It is the link that connects producers and consumers and brings production and consumption together.
About one in every six employees is involved directly in wholesaling or retailing activities.
This ratio does not take into account other employees who assist marketing through transportation, communication, and office jobs.
Marketing provides many different kinds of jobs.
These jobs require a wide range of skills and abilities.
We usually think that the primary job in marketing is selling, but there are jobs in management, advertising, market and product research, and buying.
The economic well-being of our country is determined largely by productivity, consumption, and employment.
The efficiency of marketing affects all three.
People consume many goods if marketing creates a demand.
High consumption requires high productivity to meet the wants of people, and high productivity and high-level activity in marketing combined result in high employment.
Marketing is indirectly a key to a high economic level of living for the people.

One major factor mentioned as affecting our economic well-being was

The chief emphasis is on

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The possibility of life on Mars is not dismissed even by skeptics.
They seem to share our hope that it is true.
So, it was disappointing when scientists studied photos from the early Mariner space flights in the mid-1960's.
They saw no canals, no seas, and no busy Martian engineers.
They saw no dangerous, warlike Martians as huge as skyscrapers.
All they saw were mountains, craters, cold winds, and dust storms.
It was almost as if scouts for Columbus had returned to Isabella’s court with the news that the world had turned out to be flat after all.
Hopeful astronomers reminded us that the Mariner IV had photographed a mere one percent of the Martian surface from 2,000 miles away.
In addition, the photos were taken from 2,000 miles away.
And they pointed out that the Earth-orbiting Tiros weather satellite shot over 20,000 pictures before uncovering any evidence of life on Earth.
But still, public enthusiasm for Martian exploration wilted.
Few people seemed to care about life on Mars by the time Viking I landed on the Plain of Chrise in August.

One Viking scientist, J. Richard Keefe, said that he was “disgusted” at the “blasé...apathetic” public response and the skimpy television coverage of one of the most magnificent scientific and technical accomplishments in human history.

Spreadsheet: question_text: One weather satellite was named
One of the Mariners photographed how much of the surface of Mars?
Interest in Mars diminished largely because
Spreadsheet: response_c: the photos were all black and white
Spreadsheet: response_d: nothing was brought back to earth
Spreadsheet: response_e: the media did not appreciate the accomplishment

Spreadsheet: question_text: Mention of the flat world was used to point out

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Local governments were our first governments.
A local government was established when the oldest men in a primitive tribe formed a council and the tribe chose a chief.
The tribe was seeking a better, safer life.
In the same way, the first English settlers soon realized that they needed rules and leaders after they landed at Jamestown, Virginia in 1607.
At first, the settlers had to look out for themselves.
They searched for gold, and had to find their own food and provide their own shelter.
As food supplies began to run low, and as the colonists faced hunger and disease, they saw that they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
So, they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
The colonists formed a council to make laws for the colony.
They chose Captain John Smith as president of the council.
His job was to see that the laws were carried out.
This government at Jamestown was the first local government in America.
Today, local government is still the first and most important one in our lives.
It protects our lives, our safety, and our homes, and it helps to keep our environment clean.
Local government provides us with schools, libraries, and other important services.

The Jamestown colonists formed a government because of
The best title for this selection would be
The overall goal of local government seems to be public

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 4
Random assignment is the key to experimental design.
Random assignment insures that the results of experiments are not influenced by some extraneous variable.
An extraneous variable is one that is correlated with the variable under investigation.
In contrast, correlational designs allow subjects to assign themselves to conditions.
Thus, in the cancer studies as they have been done, only people who are four-pack-a-day smokers—by their own “choice”—get into a four-pack-a-day condition.
But, the factors that make people four-pack-a-day smokers must surely make them different from typical nonsmokers in other ways.
Hence the ambiguity of interpretation in correlational designs, and hence the virtue of experimental designs.
Differences among individual subjects cannot systematically confound the results if assignment to conditions is truly random.
Put another way, the experimenter has under his control all the variables that can influence the results.
It is another question as to whether they can exactly identify these variables.
Thus, the results from experimental designs are not entirely unambiguous, but they are less ambiguous than the results from correlational designs.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The possibility of life on Mars is not dismissed even by skeptics.
They seem to share our hope that it is true.
So, it was disappointing when scientists studied photos from the early Mariner space flights in the mid-1960's.
They saw no canals, no seas, and no busy Martian engineers.
They saw no dangerous, warlike Martians as huge as skyscrapers.
All they saw were mountains, craters, cold winds, and dust storms.
It was almost as if scouts for Columbus had returned to Isabella’s court with the news that the world had turned out to be flat after all.
Hopeful astronomers reminded us that the Mariner IV had photographed a mere one percent of the Martian surface from 2,000 miles away.
In addition, the photos were taken from 2,000 miles away.
And they pointed out that the Earth-orbiting Tiros weather satellite shot over 20,000 pictures before uncovering any evidence of life on Earth.
But still, public enthusiasm for Martian exploration wilted.
Few people seemed to care about life on Mars by the time Viking I landed on the Plain of Chrise in August.

One Viking scientist, J. Richard Keefe, said that he was “disgusted” at the “blasé...apathetic” public response and the skimpy television coverage of one of the most magnificent scientific and technical accomplishments in human history.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Local governments were our first governments.
A local government was established when the oldest men in a primitive tribe formed a council and the tribe chose a chief.
The tribe was seeking a better, safer life.
In the same way, the first English settlers soon realized that they needed rules and leaders after they landed at Jamestown, Virginia in 1607.
At first, the settlers had to look out for themselves.
They searched for gold, and had to find their own food and provide their own shelter.
As food supplies began to run low, and as the colonists faced hunger and disease, they saw that they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
So, they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
The colonists formed a council to make laws for the colony.
They chose Captain John Smith as president of the council.
His job was to see that the laws were carried out.
This government at Jamestown was the first local government in America.
Today, local government is still the first and most important one in our lives.
It protects our lives, our safety, and our homes, and it helps to keep our environment clean.
Local government provides us with schools, libraries, and other important services.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 4
Random assignment is the key to experimental design.
Random assignment insures that the results of experiments are not influenced by some extraneous variable.
An extraneous variable is one that is correlated with the variable under investigation.
In contrast, correlational designs allow subjects to assign themselves to conditions.
Thus, in the cancer studies as they have been done, only people who are four-pack-a-day smokers—by their own “choice”—get into a four-pack-a-day condition.
But, the factors that make people four-pack-a-day smokers must surely make them different from typical nonsmokers in other ways.
Hence the ambiguity of interpretation in correlational designs, and hence the virtue of experimental designs.
Differences among individual subjects cannot systematically confound the results if assignment to conditions is truly random.
Put another way, the experimenter has under his control all the variables that can influence the results.
It is another question as to whether they can exactly identify these variables.
Thus, the results from experimental designs are not entirely unambiguous, but they are less ambiguous than the results from correlational designs.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Local governments were our first governments.
A local government was established when the oldest men in a primitive tribe formed a council and the tribe chose a chief.
The tribe was seeking a better, safer life.
In the same way, the first English settlers soon realized that they needed rules and leaders after they landed at Jamestown, Virginia in 1607.
At first, the settlers had to look out for themselves.
They searched for gold, and had to find their own food and provide their own shelter.
As food supplies began to run low, and as the colonists faced hunger and disease, they saw that they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
So, they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
The colonists formed a council to make laws for the colony.
They chose Captain John Smith as president of the council.
His job was to see that the laws were carried out.
This government at Jamestown was the first local government in America.
Today, local government is still the first and most important one in our lives.
It protects our lives, our safety, and our homes, and it helps to keep our environment clean.
Local government provides us with schools, libraries, and other important services.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 4
Random assignment is the key to experimental design.
Random assignment insures that the results of experiments are not influenced by some extraneous variable.
An extraneous variable is one that is correlated with the variable under investigation.
In contrast, correlational designs allow subjects to assign themselves to conditions.
Thus, in the cancer studies as they have been done, only people who are four-pack-a-day smokers—by their own “choice”—get into a four-pack-a-day condition.
But, the factors that make people four-pack-a-day smokers must surely make them different from typical nonsmokers in other ways.
Hence the ambiguity of interpretation in correlational designs, and hence the virtue of experimental designs.
Differences among individual subjects cannot systematically confound the results if assignment to conditions is truly random.
Put another way, the experimenter has under his control all the variables that can influence the results.
It is another question as to whether they can exactly identify these variables.
Thus, the results from experimental designs are not entirely unambiguous, but they are less ambiguous than the results from correlational designs.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 1
Marketing is a business activity that directs the flow of goods and services from a producer to a consumer or user.
It is the link that connects producers and consumers and brings production and consumption together.
About one in every six employees is involved directly in wholesaling or retailing activities.
This ratio does not take into account other employees who assist marketing through transportation, communication, and office jobs.
Marketing provides many different kinds of jobs.
These jobs require a wide range of skills and abilities.
We usually think that the primary job in marketing is selling, but there are jobs in management, advertising, market and product research, and buying.
The economic well-being of our country is determined largely by productivity, consumption, and employment.
The efficiency of marketing affects all three.
People consume many goods if marketing creates a demand.
High consumption requires high productivity to meet the wants of people, and high productivity and high-level activity in marketing combined result in high employment.
Marketing is indirectly a key to a high economic level of living for the people.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The possibility of life on Mars is not dismissed even by skeptics.
They seem to share our hope that it is true.
So, it was disappointing when scientists studied photos from the early Mariner space flights in the mid-1960's.
They saw no canals, no seas, and no busy Martian engineers.
They saw no dangerous, warlike Martians as huge as skyscrapers.
All they saw were mountains, craters, cold winds, and dust storms.
It was almost as if scouts for Columbus had returned to Isabella’s court with the news that the world had turned out to be flat after all.
Hopeful astronomers reminded us that the Mariner IV had photographed a mere one percent of the Martian surface from 2,000 miles away.
In addition, the photos were taken from 2,000 miles away.
And they pointed out that the Earth-orbiting Tiros weather satellite shot over 20,000 pictures before uncovering any evidence of life on Earth.
But still, public enthusiasm for Martian exploration wilted.
Few people seemed to care about life on Mars by the time Viking I landed on the Plain of Chrise in August.

One Viking scientist, J. Richard Keefe, said that he was “disgusted” at the “blasé...apathetic” public response and the skimpy television coverage of one of the most magnificent scientific and technical accomplishments in human history.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 1
Marketing is a business activity that directs the flow of goods and services from a producer to a consumer or user.
It is the link that connects producers and consumers and brings production and consumption together.
About one in every six employees is involved directly in wholesaling or retailing activities.
This ratio does not take into account other employees who assist marketing through transportation, communication, and office jobs.
Marketing provides many different kinds of jobs.
These jobs require a wide range of skills and abilities.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The possibility of life on Mars is not dismissed even by skeptics.
They seem to share our hope that it is true.
So, it was disappointing when scientists studied photos from the early Mariner space flights in the mid-1960's.
They saw no canals, no seas, and no busy Martian engineers.
They saw no dangerous, warlike Martians as huge as skyscrapers.
All they saw were mountains, craters, cold winds, and dust storms.
It was almost as if scouts for Columbus had returned to Isabella’s court with the news that the world had turned out to be flat after all.
Hopeful astronomers reminded us that the Mariner IV had photographed a mere one percent of the Martian surface from 2,000 miles away.
In addition, the photos were taken from 2,000 miles away.
And they pointed out that the Earth-orbiting Tiros weather satellite shot over 20,000 pictures before uncovering any evidence of life on Earth.
But still, public enthusiasm for Martian exploration wilted.
Few people seemed to care about life on Mars by the time Viking I landed on the Plain of Chrise in August.

One Viking scientist, J. Richard Keefe, said that he was “disgusted” at the “blasé...apathetic” public response and the skimpy television coverage of one of the most magnificent scientific and technical accomplishments in human history.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Local governments were our first governments.
A local government was established when the oldest men in a primitive tribe formed a council and the tribe chose a chief.
The tribe was seeking a better, safer life.
In the same way, the first English settlers soon realized that they needed rules and leaders after they landed at Jamestown, Virginia in 1607.
At first, the settlers had to look out for themselves.
They searched for gold, and had to find their own food and provide their own shelter.
As food supplies began to run low, and as the colonists faced hunger and disease, they saw that they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
So, they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
The colonists formed a council to make laws for the colony.
They chose Captain John Smith as president of the council.
His job was to see that the laws were carried out.
This government at Jamestown was the first local government in America.
Today, local government is still the first and most important one in our lives.
It protects our lives, our safety, and our homes, and it helps to keep our environment clean.
Local government provides us with schools, libraries, and other important services.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 4
Random assignment is the key to experimental design.
Random assignment insures that the results of experiments are not influenced by some extraneous variable.
An extraneous variable is one that is correlated with the variable under investigation.
In contrast, correlational designs allow subjects to assign themselves to conditions.
Thus, in the cancer studies as they have been done, only people who are four-pack-a-day smokers—by their own “choice”—get into a four-pack-a-day condition.
But, the factors that make people four-pack-a-day smokers must surely make them different from typical nonsmokers in other ways.
Hence the ambiguity of interpretation in correlational designs, and hence the virtue of experimental designs.
Differences among individual subjects cannot systematically confound the results if assignment to conditions is truly random.
Put another way, the experimenter has under his control all the variables that can influence the results.
It is another question as to whether they can exactly identify these variables.
Thus, the results from experimental designs are not entirely unambiguous, but they are less ambiguous than the results from correlational designs.

It is the link that connects producers and consumers and brings production and consumption together.
About one in every six employees is involved directly in wholesaling or retailing activities.
This ratio does not take into account other employees who assist marketing through transportation, communication, and office jobs.
Marketing provides many different kinds of jobs.
These jobs require a wide range of skills and abilities.
We usually think that the primary job in marketing is selling, but there are jobs in management, advertising, market and product research, and buying.
The economic well-being of our country is determined largely by productivity, consumption, and employment.
The efficiency of marketing affects all three.
People consume many goods if marketing creates a demand.
High consumption requires high productivity to meet the wants of people, and high productivity and high-level activity in marketing combined result in high employment.
Marketing is indirectly a key to a high economic level of living for the people.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 2
The possibility of life on Mars is not dismissed even by skeptics.
They seem to share our hope that it is true.
So, it was disappointing when scientists studied photos from the early Mariner space flights in the mid-1960's.
They saw no canals, no seas, and no busy Martian engineers.
They saw no dangerous, warlike Martians as huge as skyscrapers.
All they saw were mountains, craters, cold winds, and dust storms.
It was almost as if scouts for Columbus had returned to Isabella’s court with the news that the world had turned out to be flat after all.
Hopeful astronomers reminded us that the Mariner IV had photographed a mere one percent of the Martian surface from 2,000 miles away.
In addition, the photos were taken from 2,000 miles away.
And they pointed out that the Earth-orbiting Tiros weather satellite shot over 20,000 pictures before uncovering any evidence of life on Earth.
But still, public enthusiasm for Martian exploration wilted.
Few people seemed to care about life on Mars by the time Viking I landed on the Plain of Chrise in August.

One Viking scientist, J. Richard Keefe, said that he was “disgusted” at the “blasé...apathetic” public response and the skimpy television coverage of one of the most magnificent scientific and technical accomplishments in human history.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 3
Local governments were our first governments.
A local government was established when the oldest men in a primitive tribe formed a council and the tribe chose a chief.
The tribe was seeking a better, safer life.
In the same way, the first English settlers soon realized that they needed rules and leaders after they landed at Jamestown, Virginia in 1607.
At first, the settlers had to look out for themselves.
They searched for gold, and had to find their own food and provide their own shelter.
As food supplies began to run low, and as the colonists faced hunger and disease, they saw that they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
So, they needed to work together if the colony was to survive.
The colonists formed a council to make laws for the colony.
They chose Captain John Smith as president of the council.
His job was to see that the laws were carried out.
This government at Jamestown was the first local government in America.
Today, local government is still the first and most important one in our lives.
It protects our lives, our safety, and our homes, and it helps to keep our environment clean.
Local government provides us with schools, libraries, and other important services.

Spreadsheet: line_text: Passage 4
Random assignment is the key to experimental design.
Random assignment insures that the results of experiments are not influenced by some extraneous variable.
An extraneous variable is one that is correlated with the variable under investigation.
In contrast, correlational designs allow subjects to assign themselves to conditions.
Thus, in the cancer studies as they have been done, only people who are four-pack-a-day smokers—by their own “choice”—get into a four-pack-a-day condition.
But, the factors that make people four-pack-a-day smokers must surely make them different from typical nonsmokers in other ways.
Hence the ambiguity of interpretation in correlational designs, and hence the virtue of experimental designs.
Differences among individual subjects cannot systematically confound the results if assignment to conditions is truly random.
Put another way, the experimenter has under his control all the variables that can influence the results.
It is another question as to whether they can exactly identify these variables.
Thus, the results from experimental designs are not entirely unambiguous, but they are less ambiguous than the results from correlational designs.

TASK INSTRUCTIONS - PLEASE READ CAREFULLY! The goal of this study is to learn how mind wandering affects how you learn information during reading.

Mind wandering is a term used to describe what occurs when your attention wanders from a task. Sometimes when your mind wanders, you begin thinking about personal events or concerns rather than your task. At other times, your mind can wander because you are bored or tired and you don’t really know what you’re thinking about; all you know is that you are no longer thinking about your task.

Please press the space bar to continue.

In this task, you will read 4 passages and answer reading comprehension questions for each passage.

Please press the space bar to continue.

THE SET OF READING COMPREHENSION QUESTIONS FOR THAT PARTICULAR PASSAGE YOU’VE FINISHED READING WILL APPEAR AFTER EACH PASSAGE, not all together at the end. Like the sentences, once you've answered the questions you MAY NOT GO BACK TO CHANGE YOUR ANSWER.

Please press the space bar to continue.

Additionally, while you are reading you will be randomly interrupted and asked “WERE YOU MIND WANDERING WHEN YOU READ THE PREVIOUS SENTENCE?" You would have to choose either “Yes” or "No" by clicking on the appropriate option.

Please press the space bar to continue.
